= Insertion Loss Method 

The Insertion Loss Method is a testing method used in the telecommunications industry to verify the performance of connectorized cables. This method involves measuring the loss of signal strength that occurs when a connector is inserted into a cable.

To perform the Insertion Loss Method test, a signal is transmitted through the cable and the strength of the signal is measured at both ends of the cable. The connector is then inserted into the cable, and the strength of the signal is measured again. The difference between the two measurements is the insertion loss.

The purpose of the Insertion Loss Method is to ensure that the connectors used in telecom systems are functioning properly and meet industry standards. This is important because the performance of connectors can have a significant impact on the overall performance of a telecom system. By testing the performance of connectors using the Insertion Loss Method, telecom companies can ensure that their systems are functioning as intended and meeting the required standards.

In addition to verifying the performance of connectors, the Insertion Loss Method can also be used to troubleshoot problems in a telecom system. By performing Insertion Loss Method tests on different connectors within the system, technicians can identify any connectors that are not performing up to standard and take corrective action. This can help to ensure the overall reliability and performance of the telecom system.

== Purpose 

