== Requirements 

The requirements for the Insertion Loss Method test in telecom will depend on the specific standards and regulations that apply to the connectors being tested. In general, however, there are a few common requirements that are typically applied to Insertion Loss Method tests:

. The connectors being tested should be installed in their intended environment (e.g., in a conduit, on a pole, etc.). This helps to ensure that the test results are representative of the connectors' actual performance.

. The connectors should be terminated with the appropriate fittings. This may include adapters or couplers, as well as any necessary tools or equipment.

. The connectors should be tested in both directions (i.e., with the signal flowing in both directions through the connector). This helps to ensure that the connectors are functioning properly in both directions.

. The test equipment should be calibrated and properly maintained. This helps to ensure that the test results are accurate and reliable.

. The test should be performed by a trained and qualified technician. This helps to ensure that the test is performed correctly and that the results are properly interpreted.

It's worth noting that these are just a few of the requirements that may be applicable to Insertion Loss Method tests. The specific requirements will depend on the standards and regulations that apply to the connectors being tested, as well as the specific requirements of the telecom company or organization conducting the test.

== Procedure

Here is a general procedure for performing the Insertion Loss Method test in telecom:

. Gather the necessary equipment and materials:
.. Insertion Loss Method test equipment
.. Connectorized cable to be tested
.. Appropriate connectors and fittings for the cable
.. Calibration equipment (if necessary)
. Install the cable in its intended environment (e.g., in a conduit, on a pole, etc.).

. Terminate the cable with the appropriate connectors and fittings.

. Set up the Insertion Loss Method test equipment according to the manufacturer's instructions.

. Calibrate the test equipment (if necessary).

. Connect the test equipment to one end of the cable.

. Transmit a signal over the cable using the test equipment.

. Measure the strength of the signal at the other end of the cable using the test equipment.

. Record the signal strength measurement.

. Insert the connector into the cable.

. Measure the strength of the signal at the other end of the cable using the test equipment.

. Calculate the insertion loss by subtracting the second signal strength measurement from the first.

. Record the insertion loss measurement.

. Disconnect the test equipment from the cable.

. Repeat the test